 Roman East and the Inter-Religious Struggle for Success -- tConclusion -- tReligious Coexistence, Co-operation, Competition, and Conflict in Sardis and Smyrna -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tModern Authors Index -- tAncient Sources Index -- tSubject Index -- tSeries Published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press for the Canadian Corporationfor Studies in Religion/CorporationCanadienne des Sciences Religieuses -- tSeries Published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press for the Canadian Corporation for Studies in Religion/CorporationCanadienne des Sciences Religieuses0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume, one in a series of books examining religious rivalries, focuses in detail on the religious dimension of life in two particular Roman cities: Sardis and Smyrna. The essays explore the relationships and rivalries among Jews, Christians, and various Greco-Roman religious groups from the second century bce to the fourth century ce. The thirteen contributors, including seasoned scholars and promising newcomers, bring fresh perspectives on religious life in antiquity. They draw upon a wide range of archaeological, epigraphic, and literary data to investigate the complex web of relationships that existed among the religious groups of these two cities—from coexistence and cooperation to competition and conflict. To the extent that the essays investigate how religious groups are shaped by their urban settings, the book also offers insights into the material urban realities of the Roman Empire. Investigating two cities together in one volume highlights similarities and differences in the interaction of religious groups in each location. The specific focus on Sardis and Smyrna is broadened through an investigation of methodological issues involved in the study of the interaction of urban-based religious groups in antiquity. The volume will be of particular interest to scholars and advanced students in Biblical Studies, Classical Studies, and Archaeology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSardes (Ville ancienne)xReligion. 0aSardis (Extinct city)xReligion. 4aHistory. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh1 aAasgaard, Reidar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAscough, Richard S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAscough, Richard S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGaston, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammer, Keir E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarland, Philip A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHegedus, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLightstone, Jack N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, John W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCready, Wayne O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuir, Steven C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeufeld, Dietmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920924440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889209244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889209244/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete